start with product risk.

00:03:00.800 --> 00:03:04.650
And, actually, Google, I
think, as a company generally,

00:03:04.650 --> 00:03:07.486
most people at Google take
quite a bit of product risk.

00:03:07.486 --> 00:03:08.860
In other words,
you're inventing.

00:03:08.860 --> 00:03:10.570
You're bringing new
products to the world.

00:03:10.570 --> 00:03:12.486
And the way you measure
that is product market

00:03:12.486 --> 00:03:14.590
fit and traction.

00:03:14.590 --> 00:03:15.620
It's not always the way.

00:03:15.620 --> 00:03:19.080
There are other groups, other
entrepreneurs who prefer

00:03:19.080 --> 00:03:20.440
not to take product risks.

00:03:20.440 --> 00:03:24.070
So they all take a
fairly familiar product.

00:03:24.070 --> 00:03:25.432
But they will take market risks.

00:03:25.432 --> 00:03:26.890
So they'll take a
familiar product,

00:03:26.890 --> 00:03:30.600
but then they will build
it in an unfamiliar market.

00:03:30.600 --> 00:03:33.940
So just as legitimate
as a strategy,

00:03:33.940 --> 00:03:36.040
but a very, very different
sort of set of risks.

00:03:36.040 --> 00:03:38.123
Whether you're taking
product risk or market risk,

00:03:38.123 --> 00:03:41.480
you definitely also
take execution risk.

00:03:41.480 --> 00:03:43.150
So getting stuff done.

00:03:43.150 --> 00:03:46.640
And in my world, in
the investment world,

00:03:46.640 --> 00:03:47.830
we never back ideas.

00:03:47.830 --> 00:03:48.850
We back teams.

00:03:48.850 --> 00:03:51.300
We back people who
get stuff done.

00:03:51.300 --> 00:03:53.560
Which is sort of a common
misconception fueled

00:03:53.560 --> 00:03:55.880
by Dragon's Den and others.

00:03:55.880 --> 00:03:57.545
So that's what we do.

00:03:57.545 --> 00:03:58.920
And I think it's
really important

00:03:58.920 --> 00:04:00.680
to sort of start
there and ground it

00:04:00.680 --> 00:04:04.026
in this is all about people
who take risks-- as I said,

00:04:04.026 --> 00:04:06.150
whether those people are
entrepreneurs in a startup

00:04:06.150 --> 00:04:07.930
or whether they're
innovators disrupters

00:04:07.930 --> 00:04:11.010
within a big
company like Google.

00:04:11.010 --> 00:04:13.990
And then just pause
there for a second

00:04:13.990 --> 00:04:15.830
and reflect on that
because I think

00:04:15.830 --> 00:04:19.130
most of us in the
real world spend

00:04:19.130 --> 00:04:22.890
most of our time trying
to eliminate risk

00:04:22.890 --> 00:04:26.320
or at least mitigate
it and box it in.

00:04:26.320 --> 00:04:29.690
And yet we're now talking
about disrupters and innovators

00:04:29.690 --> 00:04:34.060
within a big company or startup
entrepreneurs who deliberately

00:04:34.060 --> 00:04:37.520
invite more risk into
their lives, which

00:04:37.520 --> 00:04:40.380
is a fairly bonkers thing
to do if you think about it.

00:04:40.380 --> 00:04:44.340
And in my experience,
it very rarely

00:04:44.340 --> 00:04:48.510
ends up being contained at
just professional risk, risk

00:04:48.510 --> 00:04:50.280
that I take during work.

00:04:50.280 --> 00:04:53.460
It very often-- especially for
the startup entrepreneurs--

00:04:53.460 --> 00:04:58.300
ends up being risk
