We always use these
words, but you

00:12:19.610 --> 00:12:21.360
don't think that
there's actually

00:12:21.360 --> 00:12:23.860
a correspondence in your brain.

00:12:23.860 --> 00:12:25.482
When you learn
piano, it's not just

00:12:25.482 --> 00:12:26.690
because your fingers learned.

00:12:26.690 --> 00:12:29.740
Something develops in your
brain to give you that skill.

00:12:29.740 --> 00:12:33.050
So fight and flight is
the gushing of cortisol.

00:12:33.050 --> 00:12:36.630
Then if we survived, it would
immediately go down again.

00:12:36.630 --> 00:12:40.291
And we'd go back to hunting
and back to the day job.

00:12:40.291 --> 00:12:42.040
Just like when you see
an [INAUDIBLE] film

00:12:42.040 --> 00:12:44.760
and the gazelle gets
away from a lion,

00:12:44.760 --> 00:12:47.990
it doesn't suddenly have
to go to crisis workshops

00:12:47.990 --> 00:12:49.320
or take anti-depressants.

00:12:49.320 --> 00:12:51.940
It just goes back to grazing.

00:12:51.940 --> 00:12:54.510
I have a whole thing
that these days we're

00:12:54.510 --> 00:12:57.870
always stressed because,
A, we're being bombarded

00:12:57.870 --> 00:12:59.900
by bad news day and night.

00:12:59.900 --> 00:13:01.640
The amygdala can't
if there's something

00:13:01.640 --> 00:13:04.852
dangerous behind it or something
is happening 20,000 miles away.

00:13:04.852 --> 00:13:06.060
It can't tell the difference.

00:13:06.060 --> 00:13:07.880
I'm not saying we
don't need the news,

00:13:07.880 --> 00:13:09.610
but suddenly I'm
wired because there's

00:13:09.610 --> 00:13:11.870
an earthquake in
dung-fung-fung--

00:13:11.870 --> 00:13:14.600
like I should know.

00:13:14.600 --> 00:13:16.580
Or a whale has been
beached in Malawi.

00:13:16.580 --> 00:13:17.240
What can I do?

00:13:17.240 --> 00:13:19.819
Get an airplane ticket
and a tow truck?

00:13:19.819 --> 00:13:22.360
And then when you get there, I
don't know what to do with it.

00:13:22.360 --> 00:13:22.985
You push it in.

00:13:22.985 --> 00:13:24.230
You push it out.

00:13:24.230 --> 00:13:25.030
You roll it over.

00:13:25.030 --> 00:13:25.670
You milk it.

00:13:25.670 --> 00:13:27.070
I don't know.

00:13:27.070 --> 00:13:30.530
But the enemy is this
feeling of being overwhelmed,

00:13:30.530 --> 00:13:32.010
never shuts down.

00:13:32.010 --> 00:13:32.940
I'm not good enough.

00:13:32.940 --> 00:13:34.110
I'm not fast enough.

00:13:34.110 --> 00:13:36.876
I'm not rich enough,
enough, enough.

00:13:36.876 --> 00:13:38.750
And by the way, I don't
mean to go off piece,

00:13:38.750 --> 00:13:41.630
but these things
are all invisible.

00:13:41.630 --> 00:13:43.632
There is something
visible now and none of us

00:13:43.632 --> 00:13:45.340
are using our fight
and flight-- the fact

00:13:45.340 --> 00:13:49.160
that Donald Trump might be
the leader of the free world.

00:13:49.160 --> 00:13:50.740
And what are we doing about it?

00:13:50.740 --> 00:13:52.710
This is a guy who used
to have one nose hair

00:13:52.710 --> 00:13:55.190
and wind it around his head.

00:13:55.190 --> 00:13:57.320
Now he's got an albino
ferret on his head,

00:13:57.320 --> 00:13:59.720
and we're just sitting around.

00:13:59.720 --> 00:14:02.650
The president may end up
with roadkill on his head.

00:14:02.650 --> 00:14:06.020
I'm going off the subject.

00:14:06.020 --> 00:14:09.130
And people say, is it technology
that's driving us nuts?

00:14:09.130 --> 00:14:11.320
You know I'm sick of this
because we put it there.

00:14:11.320 --> 00:14:12.550
It didn't drop from Mars.

00:14:12.550 --> 00:14:15.504
And I thank god every
day that at 2 o'clock

00:14:15.504 --> 00:14:17.170
in the morning at the
click of a finger,

00:14:17.170 --> 00:14:22.240
I can get a husband
or a chocolate bidet.

00:14:22.240 --> 00:14:22.910
And I dream.

00:14:22.910 --> 00:14:24.560
My dream is that
some day a drone

00:14:24.560 --> 00:14:26.380
will be able to come
in and shave my legs.

00:14:28.890 --> 00:14:32.140
So the problem is that
it's the speed of it.

00:14:32.140 --> 00:14:34.415
And we aren't equipped to
keep up with that speed.

00:14:37.140 --> 00:14:39.010
Humans always had
that go-getter thing.

00:14:39.010 --> 00:14:41.220
We migrated because
we were hungry.

00:14:41.220 --> 00:14:44.150
So we got up and
went to Mongolia.

00:14:44.150 --> 00:14:45.620
Then they ran out of food.

00:14:45.620 --> 00:14:47.180
We got this naturally.

00:14:47.180 --> 00:14:50.150
Then we went to America.

00:14:50.150 --> 00:14:51.950
Suddenly there was
a buffalo buffet,

00:14:51.950 --> 00:14:54.620
and we just ate
till it was extinct.

00:14:54.620 --> 00:14:55.230
We kept going.

00:14:55.230 --> 00:14:58.200
The problem is now
it's virtual migration.

00:14:58.200 --> 00:14:59.730
And the thing about
humans, again,

00:14:59.730 --> 00:15:03.930
is to understand we
never get satiated.

00:15:03.930 --> 00:15:05.550
And I think you
probably know this

00:15:05.550 --> 00:15:09.210
that every day-- is this
true-- that every day we

00:15:09.210 --> 00:15:14.900
create a quintillion
amounts of information--

00:15:14.900 --> 00:15:18.199
quintillion bytes of
information-- every day.

00:15:18.199 --> 00:15:19.240
Do you know what that is?

00:15:19.240 --> 00:15:22.290
It's a one with
18 zeros after it.

00:15:22.290 --> 00:15:24.640
So no wonder we're wired.

00:15:24.640 --> 00:15:26.230
So I'm not saying shut it off.

00:15:26.230 --> 00:15:28.655
But we have to learn some
way to navigate the noise.

00:15:31.230 --> 00:15:33.015
I was interested
in that because, A,

00:15:33.015 --> 00:15:35.580
I wasn't just getting wired,
but I have depression.

00:15:35.580 --> 00:15:37.155
So I wanted to
figure out, is there

00:15:37.155 --> 00:15:38.780
some way I don't have
to run to shrinks

00:15:38.780 --> 00:15:40.330
and give them my bank account?

00:15:40.330 --> 00:15:42.420
Is there some way I
could self-regulate?

00:15:42.420 --> 00:15:45.750
I happened to find out because
the scientific journals-- maybe

00:15:45.750 --> 00:15:47.450
you have your own
way-- that mindfulness

00:15:47.450 --> 00:15:50.360
and cognitive-based therapy
had the best results.

00:15:50.360 --> 00:15:52.880
Otherwise, I would have
been-- if it was tree-hugging,

00:15:52.880 --> 00:15:54.750
I would have taken that up.

00:15:54.750 --> 00:15:57.090
But you can actually see
it in a brain scanner.

00:15:57.090 --> 00:15:59.565
If you do a-- if you
start to practice this,

00:15:59.565 --> 00:16:00.970
the amygdala shrinks.

00:16:00.970 --> 00:16:02.470
I don't believe in
anything unless I

00:16:02.470 --> 00:16:06.090
can see it or taste it because
I can't take the fluffy stuff.

00:16:06.090 --> 00:16:08.920
So because I have an
extreme amount of dopamine.

00:16:08.920 --> 00:16:10.920
Well, I've got that
go-getter thing, which

00:16:10.920 --> 00:16:12.700
is good news because
you get great jobs,

00:16:12.700 --> 00:16:16.470
but the bad news is it makes
me crash and burn into a wall.

00:16:16.470 --> 00:16:18.070
So I hunted down
one of the founders

00:16:18.070 --> 00:16:19.780
of mindfulness-based
cognitive therapy.

00:16:19.780 --> 00:16:21.730
He was a professor at Oxford.

00:16:21.730 --> 00:16:22.720
I'm a driven woman.

00:16:22.720 --> 00:16:25.410
So I said, give me what
happens in the brain.

00:16:25.410 --> 00:16:27.080
I just don't want
to believe this.

00:16:27.080 --> 00:16:28.962
And I don't have time to sit.

00:16:28.962 --> 00:16:31.545
I don't even have time to take
a shower, so sometimes I don't.

00:16:31.545 --> 00:16:33.130
Don't tell anybody.

00:16:33.130 --> 00:16:34.284
Nobody has time.

00:16:34.284 --> 00:16:36.450
I said, so I want to know
what happens in the brain.

00:16:36.450 --> 00:16:39.500
He said, you'd have to get into
Oxford and get your master's.

00:16:39.500 --> 00:16:41.290
And so I did.

00:16:41.290 --> 00:16:43.680
And I graduated three years ago.

00:16:43.680 --> 00:16:44.740
I wish my mother knew.

00:16:44.740 --> 00:16:46.460
I'd have to dig her up.

00:16:46.460 --> 00:16:48.942
Don't say anybody I said that.

00:16:48.942 --> 00:16:52.869
That was awful.

00:16:52.869 --> 00:16:55.470
I don't know what's about
to come out of my mouth

00:16:55.470 --> 00:16:57.890
until I hear it.

00:16:57.890 --> 00:17:02.140
So that's why I
became so fascinated.

00:17:02.140 --> 00:17:04.810
At least it's a braking system.

00:17:04.810 --> 00:17:05.839
I'm sure there's others.

00:17:05.839 --> 00:17:07.200
There will be biofeedback.

00:17:07.200 --> 00:17:10.450
And we'll talk about mindfulness
like it's the dark ages.

00:17:10.450 --> 00:17:11.630
But it's all I know.

00:17:11.630 --> 00:17:14.160
So would you like to
know how it works?

00:17:14.160 --> 00:17:17.291
Because it's all I
know at this point.

00:17:17.291 --> 00:17:17.790
All right.

00:17:17.790 --> 00:17:18.670
Go with me on this.

00:17:18.670 --> 00:17:22.210
If you don't want to go with
me, get back on your computer

00:17:22.210 --> 00:17:24.660
because I know how
tempting that is.

00:17:24.660 --> 00:17:26.990
Really, I know the addiction.

00:17:26.990 --> 00:17:29.570
Believe me, I'm up at 2
o'clock in the morning.

00:17:29.570 --> 00:17:31.880
My fingers are having an
orgy on those keyboards.

00:17:31.880 --> 00:17:34.180
It's so hard to shut it off.

00:17:34.180 --> 00:17:35.310
People write, dear Ruby.

00:17:35.310 --> 00:17:36.820
I'm already on it.

00:17:36.820 --> 00:17:39.810
And then I hate them because
they don't write me back.

00:17:39.810 --> 00:17:42.070
And then I hate them
even more because then I

00:17:42.070 --> 00:17:44.250
have to answer those fuckers.

00:17:44.250 --> 00:17:48.920
I even start scraping
around to answer spam.

00:17:48.920 --> 00:17:50.450
You know what I'm talking about.

00:17:50.450 --> 00:17:53.750
So the way mindfulness works--
I'll do the scientific version

00:17:53.750 --> 00:17:55.950
because that makes
me look smart-- is,

00:17:55.950 --> 00:17:59.740
I pointed out already, we always
have the racing mind always.

00:17:59.740 --> 00:18:01.590
The racing mind is
the fight and flight

00:18:01.590 --> 00:18:03.410
because we got language now.

00:18:03.410 --> 00:18:07.570
So where we used to be vigilant
for the enemy, now the voices,

00:18:07.570 --> 00:18:09.410
the thoughts have
replaced, oh, my god, I'm

00:18:09.410 --> 00:18:10.030
going to get caught.

00:18:10.030 --> 00:18:11.290
Oh, my god, I'm not good enough.

00:18:11.290 --> 00:18:12.840
We pretty much-- my
mother was right.

00:18:12.840 --> 00:18:15.830
That's a long-playing
album in my head.

00:18:15.830 --> 00:18:18.350
So you understand
that's the amygdala.

00:18:18.350 --> 00:18:19.900
So picture it.

00:18:19.900 --> 00:18:23.510
If you take your focus to one
of your senses-- you don't have

00:18:23.510 --> 00:18:28.100
to buy them on Amazon--
taste, sound, smell,

00:18:28.100 --> 00:18:31.770
touch-- immediately the
racing thoughts calm down.

00:18:31.770 --> 00:18:32.970
You can't have both.

00:18:32.970 --> 00:18:35.010
Think of it mechanically.

00:18:35.010 --> 00:18:38.550
So because there's no words
when you feel something.

00:18:38.550 --> 00:18:40.620
So if you want to--
should I stand up--

00:18:40.620 --> 00:18:42.490
if you want to give
a taste for this--

00:18:42.490 --> 00:18:44.870
I know this is a little
baby, but just go with me.

00:18:44.870 --> 00:18:47.330
It's either gabbling
or it's a sense.

00:18:47.330 --> 00:18:48.180
Maybe I'll sit down.

00:18:48.180 --> 00:18:49.360
It's too scary.

00:18:49.360 --> 00:18:49.860
All right.

00:18:49.860 --> 00:18:52.140
So put your hands out.

00:18:52.140 --> 00:18:55.440
And when I count to three,
clap them really hard.

00:18:55.440 --> 00:18:58.700
And then just hold
them up and try

00:18:58.700 --> 00:19:00.380
to keep your mind on the sense.

00:19:00.380 --> 00:19:02.440
If you're thinking
takes over, that's cool.

00:19:02.440 --> 00:19:05.510
Take it back to the sense,
just focusing on it.

00:19:05.510 --> 00:19:11.500
So one, two, three. [CLAP]

00:19:11.500 --> 00:19:14.240
So you'll notice, you're
trying to think is it tingly?

00:19:14.240 --> 00:19:15.525
Just sense that it is.

00:19:19.050 --> 00:19:23.870
And which finger is tingling
or throbbing or it's warm?

00:19:23.870 --> 00:19:32.820
So you go, thumbs, pointing
fingers, third finger,

00:19:32.820 --> 00:19:35.680
fourth, fifth.

00:19:38.720 --> 00:19:42.720
And then gradually-- gradually--
you'll notice it fades away.

00:19:42.720 --> 00:19:44.470
Now this isn't mindfulness.

00:19:44.470 --> 00:19:49.300
It's like playing the scales
before you play Rachmaninoff.

00:19:49.300 --> 00:19:50.910
And the point of
mindfulness isn't

00:19:50.910 --> 00:19:54.190
to become a better clapper.

00:19:54.190 --> 00:19:58.330
It's the minute you start
focusing on any sense,

00:19:58.330 --> 00:20:01.690
your brain cools down, the
amygdala, the [INAUDIBLE].

00:20:01.690 --> 00:20:05.120
And that's the only way you
can watch your thoughts is

00:20:05.120 --> 00:20:07.240
if you're cool, which
is to do with resilience

00:20:07.240 --> 00:20:09.550
because until you can
cool your brain down--

00:20:09.550 --> 00:20:11.940
I don't care how you do
it-- get that cortisol down.

00:20:11.940 --> 00:20:13.450
And there's probably
Fitbits that

00:20:13.450 --> 00:20:15.200
will show you how to
do it, though they're

00:20:15.200 --> 00:20:17.220
in the dark ages, too.

00:20:17.220 --> 00:20:20.060
But the point isn't just to
notice, oh, it's gone down,

00:20:20.060 --> 00:20:22.030
but we need to
watch our thoughts.

00:20:22.030 --> 00:20:23.930
Otherwise we're sleepwalking.

00:20:23.930 --> 00:20:25.430
Because that's when
you're creative.

00:20:25.430 --> 00:20:28.750
You need to be able to focus in
on what you're thinking rather

00:20:28.750 --> 00:20:31.720
than just-- because if
you're not watching them,

00:20:31.720 --> 00:20:34.090
you won't notice when they
snare you and they get

00:20:34.090 --> 00:20:36.100
caught in that rumination.

00:20:36.100 --> 00:20:37.940
So it's as if you're the shrink.

00:20:37.940 --> 00:20:39.760
Now you watch when
they start to go.

00:20:39.760 --> 00:20:43.750
At least you've got a stopgap
especially if you're about--

00:20:43.750 --> 00:20:46.780
you're trying to-- you know
you're getting a writer's-- I

00:20:46.780 --> 00:20:48.030
get a writer's block.

00:20:48.030 --> 00:20:49.210
Pull it to a focus.

00:20:49.210 --> 00:20:51.900
And the more you do
it, the easier it gets.

00:20:51.900 --> 00:20:55.640
And I start to get a different
relationship with my thoughts.

00:20:55.640 --> 00:20:58.670
I start to name them rather
than be at the mercy of them.

00:20:58.670 --> 00:21:00.510
So sometimes I go, oh,
that's track number

00:21:00.510 --> 00:21:05.350
52, which is everybody
knows I'm a fraud.

00:21:05.350 --> 00:21:08.280
Or track number 75, which
is, they're looking at me,

00:21:08.280 --> 00:21:10.670
but they're not
really listening.

00:21:10.670 --> 00:21:14.760
Now this may be true, but
at least the minute you

00:21:14.760 --> 00:21:17.710
become the watcher, the
minute you start watching,

00:21:17.710 --> 00:21:19.525
actually the
cortisol comes down.

00:21:24.230 --> 00:21:28.120
If you want another scientific
version of why that happens,

00:21:28.120 --> 00:21:30.644
again, if you understand a
little bit about the brain,

00:21:30.644 --> 00:21:32.310
you don't have to
become a neurosurgeon,

00:21:32.310 --> 00:21:34.910
but understand
that when you take

00:21:34.910 --> 00:21:37.930
this focus from the
amygdala to the insula,

00:21:37.930 --> 00:21:39.510
there's no muscles
in your brain,

00:21:39.510 --> 00:21:42.200
but you're building
up more gray matter.

00:21:42.200 --> 00:21:43.200
Just go with me on this.

00:21:43.200 --> 00:21:45.160
Which means more and
more neural connections,

00:21:45.160 --> 00:21:48.310
which is making you resilient

00:21:48.310 --> 00:21:50.170
Let's call it the
scientific version.

00:21:50.170 --> 00:21:51.980
Let's just call it gloop.

00:21:51.980 --> 00:21:52.780
That's my name.

00:21:52.780 --> 00:21:55.990
So each time you take
the focus, that insula

00:21:55.990 --> 00:21:59.100
is getting more and more gloop.

00:21:59.100 --> 00:22:01.000
So when the shit
hits the fan, you've

00:22:01.000 --> 00:22:03.850
got that resilience, or
at least my version of it.

00:22:03.850 --> 00:22:05.760
So it's easier to
pull to a sense.

00:22:05.760 --> 00:22:07.180
You're not going to stay there.

00:22:07.180 --> 00:22:10.030
But let me just tell you, if
you're getting that red mist,

00:22:10.030 --> 00:22:12.850
and you can't think anymore,
if you learn to pull it back,

00:22:12.850 --> 00:22:14.180
you're not vegging out.

00:22:14.180 --> 00:22:16.410
But when you go back
in, just like a car

00:22:16.410 --> 00:22:18.740
or just like rebooting
your computer,

00:22:18.740 --> 00:22:21.080
you've got more resilience
than the next guy.

00:22:21.080 --> 00:22:25.630
So actually it's quite
good for business.

00:22:25.630 --> 00:22:28.170
And if you don't understand
the gloop, everything you learn

00:22:28.170 --> 00:22:30.940
is by gray matter.

00:22:30.940 --> 00:22:33.620
If you are memorizing
something, the reason you do it

00:22:33.620 --> 00:22:36.090
over and over and
over again, it's

00:22:36.090 --> 00:22:39.150
not because you're getting more
filing cabinets in your head.

00:22:39.150 --> 00:22:41.920
It's because that particular
area of the memory

00:22:41.920 --> 00:22:44.420
is building up more
and more gloop.

00:22:44.420 --> 00:22:46.290
That's how you learn the piano.

00:22:46.290 --> 00:22:48.340
That's how you learn
how to do a backhand.

00:22:48.340 --> 00:22:51.490
And by the way, you
have to practice it.

00:22:51.490 --> 00:22:54.000
Everything you learn, if you
think about it-- calculus, how

00:22:54.000 --> 00:22:56.800
to walk, how to talk,
how to pole dance--

00:22:56.800 --> 00:22:59.670
is because you repeat it
over and over and over again.

00:22:59.670 --> 00:23:01.830
It's the practice that does it.

00:23:01.830 --> 00:23:04.680
So if you want to do a
mindfulness exercise now,

00:23:04.680 --> 00:23:05.361
want to do it?

00:23:05.361 --> 00:23:05.860
All right.

00:23:05.860 --> 00:23:07.920
Now this is making more gloop.

00:23:07.920 --> 00:23:10.560
Obviously not just
today, but keep it up.

00:23:10.560 --> 00:23:11.060
All right.

00:23:11.060 --> 00:23:14.070
So, again, this is the exercise.

00:23:14.070 --> 00:23:17.840
Come away from the
back of your chair.

00:23:17.840 --> 00:23:21.140
You just do this for a minute.

00:23:21.140 --> 00:23:23.710
And by the way, nobody
has time to do this,

00:23:23.710 --> 00:23:26.487
but when you're in a queue,
when you're-- I don't know--

00:23:26.487 --> 00:23:29.070
sitting on the bus, sitting on
the-- you all have waiting time

00:23:29.070 --> 00:23:30.740
when you're walking
down the hallway.

00:23:30.740 --> 00:23:34.840
Even a minute of this becoming
aware builds the gloop.

00:23:34.840 --> 00:23:35.340
All right.

00:23:35.340 --> 00:23:38.770
So take your focus to a sense.

00:23:38.770 --> 00:23:40.670
And let's start with
the sense that's

00:23:40.670 --> 00:23:43.370
as far from your gabbling
brain as you can.

00:23:43.370 --> 00:23:46.960
So take your focus to
where are your feet.

00:23:46.960 --> 00:23:52.170
If you can, touch the ground
so you feel the contact

00:23:52.170 --> 00:23:53.330
of your foot on the ground.

00:23:53.330 --> 00:23:56.300
Everybody can do that.

00:23:56.300 --> 00:23:59.270
And you're going to want
to think, but that's cool.

00:23:59.270 --> 00:24:00.910
Just take it back to the sense.

00:24:08.290 --> 00:24:09.470
OK, let it go.

00:24:09.470 --> 00:24:12.230
And if you didn't register
anything, it doesn't matter.

00:24:12.230 --> 00:24:16.220
Now focus on where your body is
making contact with the chair.

00:24:16.220 --> 00:24:22.530
So you feel the whole
outline and the inside

00:24:22.530 --> 00:24:24.550
your skin where
it's making contact,

00:24:24.550 --> 00:24:26.346
so you really feel the
effects of gravity.

00:24:36.000 --> 00:24:37.840
So just let that focus go.

00:24:37.840 --> 00:24:40.450
And now take your focus
to the sense of sound.

00:24:40.450 --> 00:24:41.930
So all you're
doing is listening.

00:24:53.330 --> 00:24:55.470
And your mind's
going to take you.

00:24:55.470 --> 00:24:57.640
Believe me, in a
couple seconds, you're

00:24:57.640 --> 00:25:01.090
going to get snared
by your thoughts.

00:25:01.090 --> 00:25:03.246
Maybe you're thinking
about-- I don't

00:25:03.246 --> 00:25:08.804
know-- the future, the past,
a fantasy, getting angry.

00:25:08.804 --> 00:25:11.220
As soon as you notice it, you
haven't done anything wrong.

00:25:11.220 --> 00:25:12.510
You just notice it.

00:25:12.510 --> 00:25:16.100
And then that without giving
yourself a hard time at all

00:25:16.100 --> 00:25:20.064
because everybody's minds
do it, take your focus back

00:25:20.064 --> 00:25:20.605
to listening.

00:25:28.590 --> 00:25:31.750
And then your thoughts will
take you at some point.

00:25:31.750 --> 00:25:34.280
Again, don't whip
yourself about it.

00:25:34.280 --> 00:25:35.670
Just take it back again.

00:25:43.930 --> 00:25:45.810
Another sense, if
you want, is just

00:25:45.810 --> 00:25:49.180
let the sound go
and take your focus

00:25:49.180 --> 00:25:51.960
to where you notice
that you're breathing,

00:25:51.960 --> 00:25:54.510
either whatever your
area's most vivid,

00:25:54.510 --> 00:25:58.390
through the tip of your nose,
your throat, your chest,

00:25:58.390 --> 00:26:00.622
your abdomen.

00:26:00.622 --> 00:26:01.330
And stay with it.

00:26:01.330 --> 00:26:06.700
Just try to focus on where
your air is going in and out.

00:26:13.826 --> 00:26:15.450
And then your mind's
going to take you.

00:26:15.450 --> 00:26:17.910
You have to do something.

00:26:17.910 --> 00:26:20.420
You didn't do something.

00:26:20.420 --> 00:26:23.300
You should do-- whatever
you're thinking,

00:26:23.300 --> 00:26:27.250
you just go, OK, I noticed it.

00:26:27.250 --> 00:26:28.670
Good.

00:26:28.670 --> 00:26:29.400
No judgment.

00:26:29.400 --> 00:26:31.620
Go back to where
you were breathing.

00:26:31.620 --> 00:26:34.540
And if you have trouble
tracking your breath,

00:26:34.540 --> 00:26:36.130
see if you can count to five.

00:26:36.130 --> 00:26:38.050
This isn't a contest.

00:26:38.050 --> 00:26:42.260
It's easier to be more specific.

00:26:42.260 --> 00:26:46.130
So in breath, out breath is one.

00:26:46.130 --> 00:26:49.190
In breath, out breath, two.

00:26:49.190 --> 00:26:52.460
And if you lose your way, you
haven't done anything wrong,

00:26:52.460 --> 00:26:54.860
just go back to one.

00:26:54.860 --> 00:26:57.680
And if you don't get to
five, it's not a contest.

00:26:57.680 --> 00:27:00.217
So in breath, out breath, one.

00:27:20.580 --> 00:27:22.850
So another thing this
does is it teaches

00:27:22.850 --> 00:27:26.810
you to pay attention, which goes
back to resilience and risk,

00:27:26.810 --> 00:27:30.340
is that whatever else is the
racing mind, is that really,

00:27:30.340 --> 00:27:32.660
again, there's a
part in your brain--

00:27:32.660 --> 00:27:34.430
I could tell you the
name of it-- that

00:27:34.430 --> 00:27:36.860
is in charge of attention.

00:27:36.860 --> 00:27:38.740
By the way, I'm
making it simplistic.

00:27:38.740 --> 00:27:42.150
But it really is your
anterior cingulate

00:27:42.150 --> 00:27:45.630
cortex is getting the gloop
so that you really learn.

00:27:45.630 --> 00:27:47.990
You're practicing how to--
you don't do it all day.

00:27:47.990 --> 00:27:49.580
You don't do sit-ups all day.

00:27:49.580 --> 00:27:53.530
It's just a short amount
of time, even a minute.

00:27:53.530 --> 00:27:56.730
But even that has an effect when
they look in a brain scanner.

00:27:56.730 --> 00:27:59.430
So each time you
bring the focus,

00:27:59.430 --> 00:28:03.730
you're sharpening the
ability to pay attention.

00:28:03.730 --> 00:28:05.530
And people go, well,
what's with attention?

00:28:05.530 --> 00:28:06.940
I pay it, OK?

00:28:06.940 --> 00:28:08.710
Well, you don't.

00:28:08.710 --> 00:28:10.950
Actually, as humans, we
can only pay attention

00:28:10.950 --> 00:28:13.220
to something for
1.2 seconds and then

00:28:13.220 --> 00:28:17.500
we flit away because our
minds, believe it or not,

00:28:17.500 --> 00:28:19.580
are still caveman.

00:28:19.580 --> 00:28:21.180
It doesn't understand
that there's

00:28:21.180 --> 00:28:24.450
been some redecoration
for the 21st century.

00:28:24.450 --> 00:28:27.470
So really all we're geared
for is to see what's dangerous

00:28:27.470 --> 00:28:28.230
and what's safe.

00:28:28.230 --> 00:28:30.722
That's it.

00:28:30.722 --> 00:28:34.030
We really aren't equipped
to pick one toothpaste out

00:28:34.030 --> 00:28:35.770
of 5,000 choices.

00:28:35.770 --> 00:28:38.850
So it's either a
snake or it's a stick.

00:28:38.850 --> 00:28:40.630
And what also, I
think-- this, I think,

00:28:40.630 --> 00:28:43.840
is interesting-- is wherever
you pay attention defines

00:28:43.840 --> 00:28:45.419
who you are in that second.

00:28:45.419 --> 00:28:46.960
So if you're sitting
in the computer,

00:28:46.960 --> 00:28:50.260
