00:48:04.070 --> 00:48:06.520
and you really
learn to listen, it

00:48:06.520 --> 00:48:09.870
might-- maybe you'll
have group meetings--

00:48:09.870 --> 00:48:15.030
inspire you to do something
where you really hook somebody.

00:48:15.030 --> 00:48:17.190
I don't know what that is
because it's not my job.

00:48:17.190 --> 00:48:19.419
But it has to start with you.

00:48:19.419 --> 00:48:20.960
PETER READ: And we
all know what that

00:48:20.960 --> 00:48:25.830
feels like when
we're in a-- my wife

00:48:25.830 --> 00:48:28.920
is one of those people who,
if you ask my children or any

00:48:28.920 --> 00:48:31.220
of our friends, she is
one of those people who

00:48:31.220 --> 00:48:33.890
when she's present
in a conversation,

00:48:33.890 --> 00:48:35.650
she's incredibly present.

00:48:35.650 --> 00:48:37.999
And she doesn't practice
mindfulness to get there.

00:48:37.999 --> 00:48:39.332
RUBY WAX: Yeah, she's a natural.

00:48:39.332 --> 00:48:40.498
PETER READ: She's a natural.

00:48:40.498 --> 00:48:41.080
You know her.

00:48:41.080 --> 00:48:42.320
She's a natural.

00:48:42.320 --> 00:48:43.560
Some people can do that.

00:48:43.560 --> 00:48:47.810
So it is a very--
it's very precious.

00:48:47.810 --> 00:48:50.750
RUBY WAX: Maybe you ask
people what they want.

00:48:50.750 --> 00:48:55.593
And then you sculpt
what you're giving.

00:48:55.593 --> 00:48:58.700
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:48:58.700 --> 00:48:59.662
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:48:59.662 --> 00:49:02.120
I've been practicing for about,
I think, a year and a half,

00:49:02.120 --> 00:49:03.400
almost every day.

00:49:03.400 --> 00:49:05.104
And something that
I find is, even

00:49:05.104 --> 00:49:07.520
though I think in the long
term it's been very beneficial,

00:49:07.520 --> 00:49:10.390
I sometimes struggle
with increased anxiety

00:49:10.390 --> 00:49:13.446
as a result of this increased
sense of being present.

00:49:13.446 --> 00:49:15.320
Because sometimes you're
so present that when

00:49:15.320 --> 00:49:17.150
you run into these
cycles of anxiety,

00:49:17.150 --> 00:49:19.997
it just perpetrates into
more and more and more.

00:49:19.997 --> 00:49:21.080
How do you deal with that?

00:49:21.080 --> 00:49:22.510
Because it's something
that I have, like I said,

00:49:22.510 --> 00:49:24.259
found very useful over
the course of time,

00:49:24.259 --> 00:49:26.050
but then sometimes
it is very-- yeah,

00:49:26.050 --> 00:49:27.450
you're almost too present.

00:49:27.450 --> 00:49:29.150
RUBY WAX: Yeah, I got that.

00:49:29.150 --> 00:49:31.680
But, again, mindfulness
means that you're

00:49:31.680 --> 00:49:33.920
taking the temperature.

00:49:33.920 --> 00:49:35.110
You're the barometer.

00:49:35.110 --> 00:49:38.115
If it's too much-- I
always say, if you're

00:49:38.115 --> 00:49:40.240
in the midst of burnout or
if you're in depression,

00:49:40.240 --> 00:49:42.990
do not go near this.

00:49:42.990 --> 00:49:47.370
So mindfulness is-- the
big thing in bold print

00:49:47.370 --> 00:49:49.090
is be nice to yourself.

00:49:49.090 --> 00:49:49.880
Go in the gym.

00:49:49.880 --> 00:49:51.671
Maybe you can't because
you broke your arm,

00:49:51.671 --> 00:49:53.840
but go in the gym.

00:49:53.840 --> 00:49:55.990
Distract yourself.

00:49:55.990 --> 00:49:57.870
There's moments where
you need distractions,

00:49:57.870 --> 00:50:00.510
just like there's moments
when you need stress.

00:50:00.510 --> 00:50:03.910
But, again, you
don't want it to be

00:50:03.910 --> 00:50:06.740
like you listen to lovely
music or there's nothing.

00:50:06.740 --> 00:50:07.690
I meditate.

00:50:07.690 --> 00:50:10.760
Go on the tube because
you learn to tolerate.

00:50:10.760 --> 00:50:14.720
And to tolerate is the
way kids will survive.

00:50:14.720 --> 00:50:16.330
It's a muscle.

00:50:16.330 --> 00:50:18.560
But, again, you'll see
your tipping point.

00:50:18.560 --> 00:50:20.860
When it's driving
you nuts, get up.

00:50:20.860 --> 00:50:21.812
AUDIENCE: Fair enough.

00:50:21.812 --> 00:50:23.270
And, I think, a
follow-up question.

00:50:23.270 --> 00:50:26.670
You were saying before about
how you gauge co-founders

00:50:26.670 --> 00:50:29.470
in terms of their resilience and
their ability to manage stress.

00:50:29.470 --> 00:50:31.215
Who else do you see doing that?

00:50:31.215 --> 00:50:33.230
Is that something
you'd say is somewhat

00:50:33.230 --> 00:50:34.830
widespread amongst
funds and people

00:50:34.830 --> 00:50:38.510
trying to invest in start-ups,
gauging the ability of founders

00:50:38.510 --> 00:50:41.514
to be resilient to
take on leadership

00:50:41.514 --> 00:50:43.180
through to stress
management, et cetera?

00:50:43.180 --> 00:50:47.130
PETER READ: Yeah, I think
everybody who does what I do

00:50:47.130 --> 00:50:51.100
will do their own version
of that because it's

00:50:51.100 --> 00:50:52.500
sort of obvious, isn't it?

00:50:52.500 --> 00:50:55.670
Again, if in my world
it's not so much

00:50:55.670 --> 00:50:59.490
that we cherish the idea, it's
that we cherish the ability

00:50:59.490 --> 00:51:00.990
to get something done.

00:51:00.990 --> 00:51:03.990
And so how do people
get something done even

00:51:03.990 --> 00:51:06.870
when the doors all
seem to be closed?

00:51:06.870 --> 00:51:09.280
Well, then you want
to back founders

00:51:09.280 --> 00:51:11.994
who will climb through the
window if the door's closed.

00:51:11.994 --> 00:51:13.410
On your earlier
point, I was going

00:51:13.410 --> 00:51:19.390
to say there is a temptation
for-- well, a couple of points.

00:51:19.390 --> 00:51:21.480
One is that
meditation, like yoga,

00:51:21.480 --> 00:51:26.430
can sometimes start to become
competitive in some random way.

00:51:26.430 --> 00:51:27.560
How long do you do it for?

00:51:27.560 --> 00:51:32.870
All this kind of stuff, which
is generally less hopeful.

00:51:32.870 --> 00:51:36.670
And a second is a slightly
more philosophical point here,

00:51:36.670 --> 00:51:41.170
which is that I think everybody
I know who has been meditating,

00:51:41.170 --> 00:51:43.855
practicing mindfulness for
a long time comes to a point

00:51:43.855 --> 00:51:48.000
where-- and I think a
lot of Mark Williams

00:51:48.000 --> 00:51:50.920
and others did an amazing
job of helping bring it

00:51:50.920 --> 00:51:55.160
into the scientific
realm out of-- bring it

00:51:55.160 --> 00:51:58.830
into the scientific realm
and wrap it in neuroscience.

00:51:58.830 --> 00:52:01.390
But Mark and others
will also tell you

00:52:01.390 --> 00:52:04.740
that there comes a point
where actually it's helpful

00:52:04.740 --> 00:52:09.120
if it's slightly pushed
back into an ethical realm

00:52:09.120 --> 00:52:13.320
so that you're not just doing
it because it's great to shrink

00:52:13.320 --> 00:52:19.360
your amygdala, that in addition
that it is somehow helping

00:52:19.360 --> 00:52:24.080
you think about what's
good, and that it has

00:52:24.080 --> 00:52:27.740
some kind of ethical
vector through it

00:52:27.740 --> 00:52:32.154
as well as just pure ability
to focus your attention

00:52:32.154 --> 00:52:33.070
on the present moment.

00:52:33.070 --> 00:52:33.910
See what I mean?

00:52:33.910 --> 00:52:35.960
RUBY WAX: I think
that's from-- I

00:52:35.960 --> 00:52:38.130
know I put it in small
brackets, but when

00:52:38.130 --> 00:52:41.490
you notice that your
mind is flipping,

00:52:41.490 --> 00:52:46.330
part of the habit breaking
is being nice to yourself,

00:52:46.330 --> 00:52:48.690
kind, or whatever,
or compassionate.

00:52:48.690 --> 00:52:52.130
It's, again, I always think
of a horrible greeting card.

00:52:52.130 --> 00:52:53.540
But that's the training.

00:52:53.540 --> 00:52:58.750
So that when you start to
recognize how cruel you are

00:52:58.750 --> 00:53:02.400
to yourself, part of
it is to understand

00:53:02.400 --> 00:53:04.540
when somebody else
is giving you hell,

00:53:04.540 --> 00:53:06.280
they're listening
to a recording, too.

00:53:06.280 --> 00:53:09.040
So you stop taking
it so personally.

00:53:09.040 --> 00:53:12.920
So again, the point isn't to
sit on a gluten-free cushion.

00:53:12.920 --> 00:53:16.520
The point is that you're
now recognizing yourself

00:53:16.520 --> 00:53:20.810
in other people, or that we're
all in the same situation.

00:53:20.810 --> 00:53:22.680
That's, again, not
in the small print,

00:53:22.680 --> 00:53:24.320
but I always have
trouble with the C

00:53:24.320 --> 00:53:26.652
word, which is compassion.

00:53:26.652 --> 00:53:27.610
AUDIENCE: Great answer.

00:53:27.610 --> 00:53:28.110
Thank you.

00:53:28.110 --> 00:53:30.972
RUBY WAX: I think
that's a side project.

00:53:30.972 --> 00:53:32.930
AUDIENCE: I have a slightly
follow-on question.

00:53:32.930 --> 00:53:34.821
So can you talk us
through an example

00:53:34.821 --> 00:53:36.320
or give advice or
maybe tell a story

00:53:36.320 --> 00:53:39.300
of when this happened that
you get to that tipping point,

00:53:39.300 --> 00:53:41.070
you're frazzled,
you're overwhelmed,

00:53:41.070 --> 00:53:43.944
but there's still the issue
that it's not fully socially

00:53:43.944 --> 00:53:45.735
acceptable-- or sometimes
it is acceptable,

00:53:45.735 --> 00:53:47.860
but you don't feel it
is-- to put your hand up

00:53:47.860 --> 00:53:49.680
and say, I've got
too much on my plate.

00:53:49.680 --> 00:53:50.730
I can't cope.

00:53:50.730 --> 00:53:53.930
And we still-- obviously, we
work in a very accepting place,

00:53:53.930 --> 00:53:56.209
but there's still
commitments to be had.

00:53:56.209 --> 00:53:57.750
There's still meetings
to show up to.

00:53:57.750 --> 00:53:59.600
You still have to turn
up to work tomorrow

00:53:59.600 --> 00:54:01.683
even though sometimes you
don't feel like you can.

00:54:01.683 --> 00:54:04.980
And that bit is sometimes
hard to break through.

00:54:04.980 --> 00:54:08.120
PETER READ: She wrote a book
about this-- two, in fact.

00:54:08.120 --> 00:54:09.270
RUBY WAX: I know you can't.

00:54:09.270 --> 00:54:10.850
I can't stop, either.

00:54:10.850 --> 00:54:13.400
But let's say I'm doing a show.

00:54:13.400 --> 00:54:14.500
I'm doing a show.

00:54:14.500 --> 00:54:16.660
So I grab a minute backstage.

00:54:16.660 --> 00:54:17.660
Or you'll grab a minute.

00:54:17.660 --> 00:54:18.520
I don't care.

00:54:18.520 --> 00:54:20.670
There is a minute,
especially if you're going

00:54:20.670 --> 00:54:23.977
to have a meeting or something.

00:54:23.977 --> 00:54:25.560
I'm not saying stop
what you're doing.

00:54:25.560 --> 00:54:27.890
As a matter of fact,
there's now books

00:54:27.890 --> 00:54:31.650
that show you how to be
present while you're doing

00:54:31.650 --> 00:54:35.650
your work, which is noticing.

00:54:35.650 --> 00:54:37.470
It's always noticing
the state of mind

00:54:37.470 --> 00:54:40.310
and going back to maybe
looking at what you're doing.

00:54:40.310 --> 00:54:42.540
But the exercise is,
where is your mind?

00:54:42.540 --> 00:54:43.289
Bring it back.

00:54:43.289 --> 00:54:44.080
Where is your mind?

00:54:44.080 --> 00:54:45.260
Bring it back.

00:54:45.260 --> 00:54:49.740
And as far as work, when
you do go into a meeting

00:54:49.740 --> 00:54:53.360
and it's getting
tense, if you recognize

00:54:53.360 --> 00:54:56.190
when you're locking antlers
and this meeting isn't going

00:54:56.190 --> 00:54:57.830
anywhere, I wish
they would really

00:54:57.830 --> 00:55:00.370
learn to hold up a white
flag and say, we're just

00:55:00.370 --> 00:55:03.440
caught in that animal cycle.

00:55:03.440 --> 00:55:06.640
I think, again, if you
learn while you're there,

00:55:06.640 --> 00:55:08.530
and because you practiced
to cool it down--

00:55:08.530 --> 00:55:10.820
I'm sure that's why Arabs
use those beads because it's

00:55:10.820 --> 00:55:13.110
splitting their attention.

00:55:13.110 --> 00:55:18.630
If you learn to do it in
the situation-- walking,

00:55:18.630 --> 00:55:23.150
being in the gym, eating can
be a time to do the exercise.

00:55:23.150 --> 00:55:27.020
So you don't have
to take time off.

00:55:27.020 --> 00:55:30.020
Just that one minute.

00:55:30.020 --> 00:55:31.240
You can see the results.

00:55:31.240 --> 00:55:35.064
If somebody does it 3 and
1/2 hours, it already shows.

00:55:35.064 --> 00:55:36.355
Does that answer your question?

00:55:36.355 --> 00:55:37.130
AUDIENCE: Yeah, thank you.

00:55:37.130 --> 00:55:38.950
PETER READ: It is a
very hard thing to do,

00:55:38.950 --> 00:55:41.202
isn't it, to put your
hand up and say, I--

00:55:41.202 --> 00:55:43.410
RUBY WAX: You don't have to
put your hand up, though.

00:55:43.410 --> 00:55:44.159
PETER READ: Right.

00:55:44.159 --> 00:55:45.770
RUBY WAX: It's a personal thing.

00:55:45.770 --> 00:55:47.710
You don't have to
admit to anybody.

00:55:47.710 --> 00:55:49.700
Hopefully, you're
avoiding burnout

00:55:49.700 --> 00:55:51.460
by doing this kind of thing.

00:55:51.460 --> 00:55:53.990
And, again, for
technology, I know

00:55:53.990 --> 00:55:56.280
there shouldn't be a buzzer
because it'll get people

00:55:56.280 --> 00:55:59.090
into competing going,
I shut off first.

00:55:59.090 --> 00:56:02.750
But, again, if it could
be replaced by whatever

00:56:02.750 --> 00:56:06.062
it is that cools you down--
because you need a reminder.

00:56:06.062 --> 00:56:06.770
That's the thing.

00:56:06.770 --> 00:56:10.720
When we get frazzled,
how do you pull out?

00:56:10.720 --> 00:56:12.066
I think it's practice.

00:56:12.066 --> 00:56:13.290
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

